          "body": "The chapter's final block introduces the first four of the Thirty Sayings as direct commands with explicit theological grounding. The first two (22:22-23, 24-25) concern relationships: do not exploit the poor (the LORD is their advocate) and do not befriend the angry man (his ways are contagious). The alignment of these two commands is not accidental — both concern the transfer of harm to the vulnerable. The poor are vulnerable economically; the naive companion is vulnerable morally. The LORD's advocacy for the poor (22:23) applies the covenant principle that Yahweh hears the cry of the afflicted (Exodus 22:22-24; Deuteronomy 10:18). The warning against the angry companion (22:24-25) introduces the chapter's most explicit social-formation principle: character is contagious, and the pattern of association determines the pattern of life. The boundary-stone command (22:28) invokes Deuteronomy 19:14 and 27:17 — moving the ancient boundary was a form of legal theft, quietly depriving neighbors of land their ancestors had staked. Wisdom refuses complicity in systemic injustice even when no violence is involved."
