        "title": "Name above wealth — the opening thesis and its theological ground",
        "range": "22:1-4",
        "excerpt": "A good name is to be more desired than great wealth, Favor is better than silver and gold.",
        "body": "The opening verse announces the chapter's controlling value judgment: *shem tov* (a good name) outranks *osher rav* (great riches). In the ancient world, *shem* was not merely personal reputation — it was the public account of one's character, the standing one held in the community's moral memory. To lose it was to lose social existence itself. Proverbs here does not denigrate wealth; it relativizes it. Silver and gold are real goods. But *chen* (favor, grace) — the quality that makes a person winsome and trustworthy in the eyes of others — is better, because it cannot be bought and is not lost when markets fail.\n\nVerse 2 provides the theological ground beneath the opening thesis. Rich and poor 'have a common bond' — the Hebrew *pagash* means they meet, encounter one another as equals at a shared point. That point is their common Maker. The LORD did not create two categories of humanity; He created human beings, some of whom have wealth and some of whom do not. This is not a leveling of economic difference for political purposes — Proverbs acknowledges the reality of wealth differentials throughout (22:7). It is a theological claim: economic position does not determine one's standing before the Creator.\n\nVerse 4 names the alternative currency system. Humility (*anavah*) and the fear of the LORD (*yirat yehovah*) are the seedbed, and their harvest is riches (*osher*), honor (*kavod*), and life (*chay*) — the same three goods the world pursues through wealth accumulation. The wisdom tradition's point is not that wealth is bad but that its root matters. Wealth built on the fear of the LORD is durable; wealth pursued as an end in itself is *osher* without *shem* — money without character.\n\nJohn Calvin, commenting on Proverbs 3:16 (which carries identical vocabulary), observes that Proverbs consistently presents the fear of the LORD as the only foundation from which genuine human flourishing flows. The chapter's opening four verses form a complete argument: name exceeds wealth (22:1); God levels the human hierarchy (22:2); danger and protection operate on the same principle (22:3); and the fear of the LORD is where true wealth originates (22:4).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shem tov* (good name) — the same construction used of God's own name in Exodus 34:5-6. *Anavah* (humility) appears rarely in the OT; compare Zephaniah 2:3 and Numbers 12:3 (Moses described as very *anav*). *Osher* in v.1 (great riches) and v.4 (riches as reward) is the same word — the chapter begins and ends the opening unit with the same noun, but the source has changed."
