        "number": 3,
        "title": "The preamble to the Thirty Sayings — wisdom aimed at trust in Yahweh",
        "range": "22:17-21",
        "excerpt": "Incline your ear and hear the words of the wise, And apply your mind to my knowledge; So that your trust may be in the Lord.",
        "body": "The shift at verse 17 is one of the most significant in the book of Proverbs. The teacher addresses the student directly, issuing the imperative 'incline your ear' (*natah oznekha*) — a posture of deliberate, bodily attentiveness. The physical metaphor is not accidental: wisdom requires a reorientation of the whole person, not merely the intellect. 'Apply your mind to my knowledge' (*sit libbeka*) uses the word *lev* (heart/mind) — the organ of will, decision, and affective orientation in Hebrew anthropology. True learning, for the wisdom tradition, is not information transfer but heart-transformation.\n\nThe three stated purposes of the Thirty Sayings form a descending order of specificity. First, the wisdom will be pleasant when internalized and ready on the lips (22:18) — it is a delight, not a burden, and it prepares the student to speak well in the moment. Second, it aims at equipping the student to know 'the certainty of the words of truth' (22:21) and to answer 'him who sent you' — pointing to a context of public service, diplomatic representation, or royal court administration. Third, and governing both: the whole program exists 'so that your trust may be in the LORD' (22:19). This telos is determinative. All the practical wisdom of the Thirty Sayings — about protecting the poor, avoiding the angry, refusing debt guarantees, respecting boundaries — ultimately aims not at social competence but at a life of *mivtach* (trust, confidence) in Yahweh.\n\nThe parallel with the Egyptian Instruction of Amenemope has occupied scholars since Adolf Erman's 1924 identification. Both texts are organized around thirty chapters/sayings; several specific instructions are closely parallel (e.g., Amenemope ch. 6 and Proverbs 22:22-23; Amenemope ch. 9 and Proverbs 23:10-11). Conservative scholars — Derek Kidner, Bruce Waltke, Tremper Longman III — argue for literary dependence in one direction or the other, but consistently note that Proverbs transforms every borrowed insight by grounding it in the covenant name of Yahweh. The LORD is not merely a moral guarantor added to social wisdom; He is the source from which the wisdom flows and the goal toward which the student is being aimed.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Natah* (incline) — to stretch, extend, bend toward; a physical posture of attentiveness. *Mivtach* (trust, v.19) — the place where one leans, one's support; related to *batach*, the word for trusting security used throughout Psalms (Ps. 62:8). *Shilshom* (v.20, 'excellent things' / 'thirty sayings') — the Hebrew is debated; NASB 1995 renders 'excellent things,' but the LXX and many modern versions read 'thirty sayings,' following the parallel with Amenemope."
